content:
When your customers send an email to a support address, such as support@mycompany.com, your email provider forwards the email to Salesforce. Configuring email forwarding correctly is important for Email-to-Case to attach emails and responses to related cases.

Email-to-Case uses information in the email headers to match an email to a case. If your email system's forwarding changes the headers, Email-to-Case can't identify the related case and add the email to the thread.

To allow Email-to-Case to thread emails to cases correctly, follow these general guidelines:

Configure one routing address to use in forwarding.
Avoid defining aliases that map to the same Email-to-Case service address.
Avoid email rules that add disclaimers or tags before or after the email subject.

The steps to set up forwarding depend on your email provider. Ask your email admin to set up forwarding in the Exchange Admin Center.

For Microsoft Exchange 365, create a contact with the email service address generated in Salesforce as the email address.
Configure forwarding using options like Full Inbox Forwarding or Mail Flow Rules that preserve headers during forwarding.

Because user-applied rules cause header changes that break threading, we don't recommend users creating rules in Outlook settings. If a user configures a forwarding rule, Email-to-Case can't identify the sender because the mail system strips out the original sender address.

Distribution Lists are also an option to forward emails to Email-to-Case. Create a distribution group and add the email contact created as a member.

See Add Routing Addresses for Email-to-Case or Microsoft 365 Support for more information.
title: Guidelines for Email System Forwarding with Email-to-Case
